out_desc_tool: The acquisition measure was the Math Operations Test-Revised (Fuchs, Fuchs, Hamlett, & Stecker, 1991), which systematically samples problems across Grades 1 through 6 from the operations portion of the Tennessee curriculum (i.e., addition, subtraction, multiplication, and division of whole numbers, decimals, and fractions). Pupils are provided directions in standard format and have 10 min to complete 50 problems. Performance was scored as number of correct problems, not digits. Criterion validity with respect to the math computation subtest of the Stanford Achievement Test was .78. Internal consistency reliability (Cronbach’s alpha) was .86. Percentage of agreement on 60 protocols distributed evenly across testings, was 99.7.
out_desc_math: The acquisition measure was the Math Operations Test-Revised (Fuchs, Fuchs, Hamlett, & Stecker, 1991), which systematically samples problems across Grades 1 through 6 from the operations portion of the Tennessee curriculum (i.e., addition, subtraction, multiplication, and division of whole numbers, decimals, and fractions). Pupils are provided directions in standard format and have 10 min to complete 50 problems. Performance was scored as number of correct problems, not digits. Criterion validity with respect to the math computation subtest of the Stanford Achievement Test was .78. Internal consistency reliability (Cronbach’s alpha) was .86. Percentage of agreement on 60 protocols distributed evenly across testings, was 99.7.

out_desc_tool: The Comprehensive Mathematics Test (Fuchs et al., 1995), systematically samples problems to represent the Tennessee mathematics curriculum in Grades 1-6. The Operations portion of this test includes 50 mathematical operation problems, the Concepts/Applications portion presents students with 50 concept and application questions. Performance is scored as number of correct problems.
out_desc_math: The Comprehensive Mathematics Test (Fuchs et al., 1995), systematically samples problems to represent the Tennessee mathematics curriculum in Grades 1-6. The Operations portion of this test includes 50 mathematical operation problems, the Concepts/Applications portion presents students with 50 concept and application questions. Performance is scored as number of correct problems.

out_desc_tool: Comprehensive Reading Assessment Battery (CRAB). The CRAB (L. S. Fuchs, Fuchs, & Maxwell, 1988) makes use of four 400-word traditional folktales. The folktales were rewritten by Jenkins et al. (1986) to approximate a second- to third-grade readability level (Fry, 1968), while preserving their meaning. For the number of questions correct, students respond aloud to 10 comprehension questions read to them by the examiner, who records their answers. Questioning is terminated after 5 consecutive incorrect answers. Student performance is scored as the number of questions answered correctly, averaged across two 10-question samples.
out_desc_red: Comprehensive Reading Assessment Battery (CRAB). The CRAB (L. S. Fuchs, Fuchs, & Maxwell, 1988) makes use of four 400-word traditional folktales. The folktales were rewritten by Jenkins et al. (1986) to approximate a second- to third-grade readability level (Fry, 1968), while preserving their meaning. For the number of questions correct, students respond aloud to 10 comprehension questions read to them by the examiner, who records their answers. Questioning is terminated after 5 consecutive incorrect answers. Student performance is scored as the number of questions answered correctly, averaged across two 10-question samples.

out_tit_tool: TE_PRI VERB TE G2 English writing
out_desc_tool: Post-test mean scores of second grade students’ writing prompts. Each essay was graded by three raters using the 6+1 traits writing assessment model, who assigned a numerical value from 1 (lowest score) to 5 (highest score) for each of the six traits—ideas, organization, voice, word choice, sentence fluency, and conventions. Then, the six scores (one for each trait) of all three raters (which totaled 18 scores for each student) were averaged in order to determine a final mean score for each student.
out_type_tool: ['Toolkit primary outcome', 'Writing and spelling primary outcome.']

out_desc_tool: Four parallel versions of a spelling test were used. The spelling test (dictaction of words) consisted of 40 words. The maximum number of mistakes was 48. There were three categories of words  1. words subject to certain spelling rules, e. g. Dutch teen (singular) — tenen (plural), where pronounciation of the vowel remains the same  2. words that are pronounced as they are written, e.g. tin and 3. words which we will call 'knowledge words', i.e. words the spelling of which has to be learnt, e.g. in English 'knight' instead of 'nite'. Reliability of the spelling test — determined by means of two random parallel tests — was .93, the internal consistency was .90.
out_type_tool: ['Toolkit primary outcome', 'Writing and spelling primary outcome.']

out_desc_tool: For each grade level three parallel versions of a spelling test were used. The spelling test (dictation of words) consisted of 30 words for grade 2, and 40 words for grades 4 and 6. Naturally, these tests consisted of words that were typical for spelling instruction at each of the three grade levels. Reliability scores (Pearsons r) of the spelling tests for the grades 2, 4 and 6 were .79, .80 and .89 respectively  the internal consistency scores (Cronbach's alpha)  .81, .77 and .84. For grade 6 an additional test of spelling of verbs (Assink, 1983)
out_type_tool: ['Toolkit primary outcome', 'Writing and spelling primary outcome.']

These comprise a total of 35 criteria relating to two 'aspects' of writing (Choice and Use of Language, and Selection and Organisation of Ideas) and their associated technical 'skills' (Spelling and Punctuation respectively), at five developmental levels labelled A (lowest) to E
